<main class="wrap" id="main">

  <!-- ============ OBJECTIVES ============ -->
  <section id="objectives">
    <p class="eyebrow">Backward designed from the application</p>
    <h2>Learning objectives</h2>
    <p class="lead">These five objectives were derived from the Week 1 notes and scoped to the high-yield set for this session. Review and adjust before posting. All objectives are anatomy only, with no physiology mechanism included.</p>
    <ol class="objectives">
      <li>Trace a secreted protein through the endomembrane system from rough ER to exocytosis, and match cell organelles and surface specializations to the jobs they perform.</li>
      <li>Differentiate the parietal and visceral layers of the three serous membranes, and map the four mediastinal compartments to one key structure each.</li>
      <li>Classify abdominopelvic organs as intraperitoneal or retroperitoneal using SADPUCKER, and predict how that relationship changes where bleeding or pain presents.</li>
      <li>Classify epithelial and connective tissues by their naming axes, and match each tissue and cell junction to its structural function.</li>
      <li>Order the layers of the skin and the five epidermal strata, and map burn depth and injection depth onto the layers involved.</li>
    </ol>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ PREWORK ============ -->
  <section id="prework">
    <p class="eyebrow">Complete before class</p>
    <div class="prework-head">
      <h2>Prework checklist</h2>
      <span class="progress-tag" id="pwProgress">0 of 5 complete</span>
    </div>
    <p class="lead">Each item lists a time estimate and a written completion criterion. Arrive having produced the written output named under each item. The iRAT assumes every item below is done.</p>

    <div class="pw-item" data-pw="1">
      <input type="checkbox" id="pw1" aria-label="Mark prework item 1 complete">
      <div class="pw-body">
        <h4>1. Watch the Language of Anatomy and Body Cavities videos, read Week 1 Notes pp. 3 to 10</h4>
        <p class="crit"><b>Completion:</b> In writing, name every subdivision of the dorsal and ventral cavities, and list the four mediastinal compartments with one structure in each.</p>
        <div class="pw-meta"><span class="chip time">35 min</span><span class="chip">Cavities, mediastinum, serous membranes</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pw-item" data-pw="2">
      <input type="checkbox" id="pw2" aria-label="Mark prework item 2 complete">
      <div class="pw-body">
        <h4>2. Watch the Cell Anatomy video, read pp. 11 to 13</h4>
        <p class="crit"><b>Completion:</b> Write the ordered path of a secreted protein from rough ER to exocytosis, and list two membranous and two non membranous organelles with their jobs.</p>
        <div class="pw-meta"><span class="chip time">25 min</span><span class="chip">Cell anatomy, endomembrane system</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pw-item" data-pw="3">
      <input type="checkbox" id="pw3" aria-label="Mark prework item 3 complete">
      <div class="pw-body">
        <h4>3. Watch the Histology video, read pp. 14 to 18</h4>
        <p class="crit"><b>Completion:</b> Build a table of the four tissue types with function, one location, and one defining feature, and classify epithelium on both naming axes.</p>
        <div class="pw-meta"><span class="chip time">35 min</span><span class="chip">Epithelial and connective tissue</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pw-item" data-pw="4">
      <input type="checkbox" id="pw4" aria-label="Mark prework item 4 complete">
      <div class="pw-body">
        <h4>4. Watch the Integumentary video, read pp. 19 to 21</h4>
        <p class="crit"><b>Completion:</b> List the five epidermal strata deep to superficial, and map first, second, and third degree burns onto the skin layers each one reaches.</p>
        <div class="pw-meta"><span class="chip time">25 min</span><span class="chip">Integumentary system</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="pw-item" data-pw="5">
      <input type="checkbox" id="pw5" aria-label="Mark prework item 5 complete">
      <div class="pw-body">
        <h4>5. SADPUCKER self quiz</h4>
        <p class="crit"><b>Completion:</b> From memory, write all nine retroperitoneal structures, and note the parts that are exceptions, the first part of the duodenum, the tail of the pancreas, and the transverse and sigmoid colon.</p>
        <div class="pw-meta"><span class="chip time">10 min</span><span class="chip">Retroperitoneum</span></div>
      </div>
    </div>
    <p class="reading" style="font-size:14px;color:var(--teal-text);margin-top:14px;">Total estimated prework: about 2 hours 10 minutes. Checkbox state saves on this device only.</p>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ iRAT ============ -->
  <section id="irat">
    <p class="eyebrow">Readiness assurance, individual</p>
    <h2>iRAT</h2>
    <p class="lead">Ten items, each one built to pull together two to four concepts at once. None can be answered by recalling a single fact. Every item asks you to read across systems, peritoneal relationships against cavity access, organelles against gland type, strata against cell type, so the test reasons like anatomy rather than marching topic by topic. The concept tag under each number names what the item integrates. Answer individually first, then keep this same set for the team round.</p>

    <div class="q" data-q="1">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q1</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Serous layers + mediastinum + access route</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A fluid collection forms around the heart, in the space between the parietal and visceral layers of the serous membrane. Which option correctly identifies that space, the mediastinal compartment the heart sits in, and the procedure used to drain it?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>The fluid lies between the visceral and parietal pleura in the anterior mediastinum, drained by thoracentesis</li>
        <li>The fluid lies in the pericardial cavity in the superior mediastinum, drained by paracentesis</li>
        <li>The fluid lies in the pericardial cavity between the parietal and visceral serous pericardium in the middle mediastinum, drained by pericardiocentesis</li>
        <li>The fluid lies between the epicardium and the fibrous pericardium in the posterior mediastinum, drained by lumbar puncture</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="2">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q2</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Quadrant map + peritoneal relationship + bleed behavior</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A wound enters the left upper quadrant. Two organs there differ in their peritoneal relationship, and that difference predicts how blood from each would behave. Which pairing is correct?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>The spleen is intraperitoneal, so its blood spreads freely; the left kidney is retroperitoneal, so its blood stays contained and presents as flank pain</li>
        <li>The spleen is retroperitoneal, so its blood stays contained; the left kidney is intraperitoneal, so its blood spreads freely</li>
        <li>Both the spleen and the left kidney are intraperitoneal, so blood from either spreads freely through the cavity</li>
        <li>Both the spleen and the left kidney are retroperitoneal, so both present only as flank pain</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="3">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q3</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Epithelial class + anchoring structure + avascular property</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A surface must protect against heavy abrasion, sits on connective tissue it is anchored to, and has no blood vessels of its own. Which option correctly describes the epidermis: its tissue classification, what anchors it, and how it gets its blood supply?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Simple squamous epithelium anchored by a mucous membrane, fed by its own capillaries</li>
        <li>Transitional epithelium anchored by tight junctions, richly vascular</li>
        <li>Pseudostratified columnar epithelium anchored by a mesentery, avascular</li>
        <li>Stratified squamous epithelium anchored to the basement membrane, avascular and fed by diffusion from the dermis</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="4">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q4</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Organelles + gland duct type + release mode</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A gland cell builds a protein product, packages it through the Golgi into secretory vesicles, releases it intact, and has no duct. Which set correctly names its prominent organelles, the gland's duct classification, and its release mode?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Smooth ER prominent; exocrine; holocrine release</li>
        <li>Rough ER and Golgi prominent; endocrine; merocrine release</li>
        <li>Free ribosomes only; endocrine; apocrine release</li>
        <li>Rough ER prominent; exocrine; holocrine release</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="5">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q5</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Epidermal strata + cell types + healing</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A burn blisters into the dermis but spares the deepest epidermal layer. Which layer's survival lets the epidermis regenerate, and which epidermal cell does the regenerating?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>The stratum corneum survives, and melanocytes regenerate the epidermis</li>
        <li>The stratum lucidum survives, and dendritic (Langerhans) cells regenerate the epidermis</li>
        <li>The stratum basale survives, and keratinocytes divide there to regenerate the epidermis</li>
        <li>The stratum granulosum survives, and tactile (Merkel) cells regenerate the epidermis</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="6">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q6</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Connective subtype + fiber arrangement + germ layer + failure mode</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A structure is strong in one direction because of parallel collagen, arises from the middle germ layer like most connective tissue, and tears when twisted rather than pulled straight. Which structure and classification fit all three clues?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>A tendon of dense regular connective tissue from mesoderm</li>
        <li>A tendon of dense irregular connective tissue from ectoderm</li>
        <li>The dermis of dense regular connective tissue from endoderm</li>
        <li>A ligament of areolar connective tissue from mesoderm</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="7">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q7</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Two junctions + cytoskeletal link + protein + location</span></div>
      <p class="stem">Two junctions both use cadherins but do different jobs: one forms an adhesion belt linked to microfilaments, the other forms plaques linked to intermediate filaments that resist pulling in the epidermis and cardiac muscle. Which pairing names them correctly?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Tight junction (belt, microfilaments) and gap junction (plaques, intermediate filaments)</li>
        <li>Adherens junction (belt, microfilaments) and desmosome (plaques, intermediate filaments)</li>
        <li>Desmosome (belt, microfilaments) and hemidesmosome (plaques, intermediate filaments)</li>
        <li>Gap junction (belt, microfilaments) and tight junction (plaques, intermediate filaments)</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="8">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q8</span><span class="dok">DOK 2</span><span class="qtopic">Regional term + directional term + imaging plane</span></div>
      <p class="stem">A wound is charted on the anterior, distal forearm, and a CT is ordered through that level. Which line correctly names the region, the meaning of distal, and the imaging plane the CT slice produces?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Brachial region; distal means closer to the trunk; the CT slice is a frontal section</li>
        <li>Antebrachial region; proximal means farther from the trunk; the CT slice is a sagittal section</li>
        <li>Carpal region; distal means closer to the shoulder; the CT slice is an oblique section</li>
        <li>Antebrachial region; distal means farther from the trunk; the CT slice is a transverse section</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="9">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q9</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Serous membrane build + tissue type + membrane comparison</span></div>
      <p class="stem">The serous membranes that line the ventral cavities are built from a specific epithelium over connective tissue. Which option correctly names that tissue and explains how a serous membrane differs from a synovial membrane?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Simple squamous epithelium, the mesothelium, over areolar connective tissue; it differs from the synovial membrane, which is connective tissue only with no epithelium</li>
        <li>Stratified squamous epithelium over dense connective tissue; it is the same construction as the synovial membrane</li>
        <li>Pseudostratified epithelium over adipose tissue; it differs from the cutaneous membrane only by location</li>
        <li>Transitional epithelium over reticular tissue; it is identical to a mucous membrane</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="10">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q10</span><span class="dok">DOK 3</span><span class="qtopic">Quadrant pattern + peritoneal relationship + cavity access</span></div>
      <p class="stem">An older adult has left lower quadrant pain, and separately a needle is planned to sample the peritoneal cavity. Which line correctly names the likely condition, the peritoneal relationship of the organ involved, and the procedure that samples that cavity?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Appendicitis; the cecum is intraperitoneal; the peritoneal cavity is sampled by thoracentesis</li>
        <li>Diverticulitis; the sigmoid colon is intraperitoneal; the peritoneal cavity is sampled by paracentesis</li>
        <li>Diverticulitis; the descending colon is retroperitoneal; the peritoneal cavity is sampled by pericardiocentesis</li>
        <li>Splenic injury; the spleen is intraperitoneal; the peritoneal cavity is sampled by lumbar puncture</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <h3>Additional items</h3>
    <p class="reading" style="font-size:14px;">Two more items, ready to swap in for any two above to hold the set at ten, or to run as eleven and twelve. Item 11, the arrector pili, is covered in the Week 1 prework. Item 12, melanin types and skin color, reaches past the Week 1 notes and is held at the observational, pigment level with no physiology mechanism. Add a matching prework line before using it in a graded RAT.</p>

    <div class="q" data-q="11">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q11</span><span class="dok">DOK 2</span><span class="qtopic">Accessory structure + muscle tissue type + control</span></div>
      <p class="stem">Cold air raises goosebumps, the small bumps that appear when tiny muscles in the skin contract and pull the hairs upright. Which option correctly names that muscle, its muscle tissue type, and whether it is under voluntary or involuntary control?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>The arrector pili; smooth muscle; involuntary</li>
        <li>The arrector pili; skeletal muscle; voluntary</li>
        <li>The hair root plexus; smooth muscle; involuntary</li>
        <li>The erector spinae; skeletal muscle; voluntary</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="12">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q12</span><span class="dok">DOK 2</span><span class="qtopic">Melanin types + sources of skin color + diagnostic color</span></div>
      <p class="stem">Skin color comes from three sources: the melanin made by melanocytes, the carotene in the tissue, and the blood in the dermal vessels showing through the epidermis. Melanin itself comes in two forms. Which option correctly names the two types of melanin and matches a diagnostic skin color to what you are seeing?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Eumelanin and carotene are the two melanins, and cyanosis is the result of excess melanin</li>
        <li>Melanin and hemoglobin are the two melanins, and pallor is the result of extra carotene</li>
        <li>Eumelanin, brown to black, and pheomelanin, red to yellow, are the two melanins, and a bluish color (cyanosis) is the dark blood in the dermal vessels showing through the thin epidermis</li>
        <li>Pheomelanin and bilirubin are the two melanins, and redness is the result of melanin loss</li>
      </ol>
    </div>

    <div class="q" data-q="13">
      <div class="qhead"><span class="qnum">Q13</span><span class="dok">DOK 2</span><span class="qtopic">Directional terms + mediastinal borders + bounding structures</span></div>
      <p class="stem">The mediastinum sits between the two pleural cavities, bounded on every side by a named structure. Which option correctly matches each border, given by its directional term, to the structure that forms it?</p>
      <ol class="opts">
        <li>Anterior, the bodies of the thoracic vertebrae; posterior, the sternum; inferior, the thoracic inlet</li>
        <li>Anterior, the sternum; posterior, the bodies of the thoracic vertebrae; inferior, the diaphragm</li>
        <li>Superior, the diaphragm; inferior, the thoracic inlet; lateral, the sternum</li>
        <li>Anterior, the diaphragm; posterior, the mediastinal pleura; superior, the thoracic vertebrae</li>
      </ol>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ tRAT ============ -->
  <section id="trat">
    <p class="eyebrow">Readiness assurance, team</p>
    <h2>tRAT</h2>
    <p class="lead">Teams answer the same ten items above by consensus, then reveal each answer simultaneously. Use scratch off cards or held up letter cards so every team commits at the same moment. Because each item integrates several concepts, expect the team talk to run longer per item than a recall quiz would. The full per option rationale for all ten items lives in the Answer center below, kept hidden until you reveal it, so you can screen share the iRAT without exposing keys.</p>
    <div class="callout navy">
      <h4>Run order for the team round</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">Teams discuss and lock one answer per item, reveal simultaneously, then appeal any item they can defend from the notes. Hand scoring follows your usual scale. Walk only the items that split the room, the Answer center flags the likely split items.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ APPLICATION ============ -->
  <section id="application">
    <p class="eyebrow">4S application exercise &middot; intermediate clinical reasoning</p>
    <h2>Application: where is the bleed</h2>
    <p class="lead">One shared problem, one specific committed choice, revealed simultaneously. The reasoning is purely anatomical: peritoneal relationships, serous cavities, and the boundary between the thoracic and abdominopelvic cavities. No physiology mechanism is required.</p>

    <div class="stimulus">
      <h3>Stimulus</h3>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">A 24 year old arrives after a single stab wound to the <b>left flank</b>, entry point just below the 12th rib and posterior to the midaxillary line. The abdomen is soft and not distended. Tenderness is sharply localized to the left flank and the left side of the back. Bruising tracks toward the flank rather than spreading across the belly. A focused scan reports a collection of fluid that does not move freely with patient position changes and sits against the posterior body wall on the left.</p>
      <div class="vitals">
        <div><span class="label">Wound site</span>Left flank, below 12th rib, posterior to midaxillary line</div>
        <div><span class="label">Abdomen</span>Soft, not distended, no shifting dullness described</div>
        <div><span class="label">Tenderness</span>Localized to left flank and back</div>
        <div><span class="label">Fluid on scan</span>Posterior, left, does not move freely with position</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="callout terra" style="margin-top:18px;">
      <h4>Trigger: commit to one answer</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">Based on the wound location and the pattern of findings, which single anatomical relationship best explains the source of the collection? Each team locks <b>one</b> letter and reveals it at the same moment as every other team.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="choice-options">
      <div class="choice"><span class="clabel">A. Retroperitoneal source</span><p class="cdesc">The blade tracked into the retroperitoneum and struck a SADPUCKER structure, the left kidney or the aorta and IVC, so blood is trapped behind the parietal peritoneum and presents as flank and back tenderness.</p></div>
      <div class="choice"><span class="clabel">B. Intraperitoneal source</span><p class="cdesc">The blade reached the spleen, an intraperitoneal organ in the left upper quadrant, so blood should spread freely through the peritoneal cavity and irritate it broadly.</p></div>
      <div class="choice"><span class="clabel">C. Pleural source</span><p class="cdesc">Because the diaphragm domes upward and the wound sits below the 12th rib, the blade may have crossed the diaphragm into the left pleural cavity, making this a thoracic injury wearing an abdominal entry point.</p></div>
    </div>

    <h3>Branch questions, one reasoning path each</h3>
    <p class="reading" style="font-size:14px;">After the simultaneous reveal, teams defend their committed letter using the branch that matches their choice, then respond to the other two.</p>

    <div class="branch">
      <span class="btag">Branch A &middot; the retroperitoneal path</span>
      <h4>If you chose A, defend it from the anatomy.</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">Which two findings in the stimulus point to a retroperitoneal source rather than an intraperitoneal one, and which SADPUCKER structures sit in the left flank in the path of this wound? Tie your answer to LO3.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="branch">
      <span class="btag">Branch B &middot; the intraperitoneal path</span>
      <h4>If you chose B, defend it from the anatomy.</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">The spleen sits in the left upper quadrant and is intraperitoneal. What would you expect the abdomen and the fluid pattern to look like if the spleen were the source, and which single finding in the stimulus argues against free intraperitoneal blood? Tie your answer to LO2 and LO3.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="branch">
      <span class="btag">Branch C &middot; the pleural path</span>
      <h4>If you chose C, defend it from the anatomy.</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0;">Explain how a wound below the 12th rib can enter the thoracic cavity, naming the boundary structure involved and the cavity reached. Which drainage procedure follows from a pleural source, and how does it differ from the procedure for an intraperitoneal collection? Tie your answer to LO2.</p>
    </div>

    <div class="callout navy" style="margin-top:18px;">
      <h4>How this exercise satisfies the 4S framework</h4>
      <ul class="plain" style="margin:0;">
        <li><b>Significant problem.</b> Localizing a penetrating flank injury by anatomical compartment is a real problem clinicians face, and pre med students recognize it as professionally meaningful.</li>
        <li><b>Same problem.</b> Every team works the identical stimulus and the identical committed choice. No team gets a different scenario.</li>
        <li><b>Specific choice.</b> Teams commit to one letter, A, B, or C, from a narrow defined set. The task is a commitment, not an open ended discussion.</li>
        <li><b>Simultaneous reporting.</b> All teams reveal their letter at the same moment using held up cards or a single timed submission.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>

    <div class="callout">
      <h4>Where the defensible disagreement lives</h4>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:0 0 8px;">At least three options carry a defensible argument, which is what drives the cross team debate:</p>
      <ul class="plain" style="margin:0;">
        <li><b>A is defensible</b> because the left kidney is retroperitoneal, the fluid does not move freely and sits against the posterior wall, and the pain is localized to the flank and back, the classic retroperitoneal pattern from the notes.</li>
        <li><b>B is defensible</b> because the spleen sits in the left upper quadrant near this wound, and a team that weights organ proximity over the fluid behavior can argue for an intraperitoneal source.</li>
        <li><b>C is defensible</b> because a sophisticated team reads the rib level and the upward dome of the diaphragm and argues the blade crossed into the pleural cavity, a real trap for a low posterior wound.</li>
      </ul>
      <p class="reading" style="margin:8px 0 0;">The findings as written tilt toward A, the fluid that does not move freely and sits posteriorly is the retroperitoneal signature, but a well prepared team can hold B or C and defend it. Push teams to name the single finding that would flip their vote.</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- ============ FACILITATION ============ -->
  <section id="facilitation">
    <p class="eyebrow">Instructor support &middot; experienced facilitator</p>
    <h2>Facilitation guide</h2>

    <h3>Sixty minute timing</h3>
    <ul class="timeline">
      <li><span class="clock">0:00 to 0:12</span><span class="what"><b>iRAT.</b> Individual answers to all ten integrative items. Use the 12 minute preset on the toolbar timer.</span></li>
      <li><span class="clock">0:12 to 0:24</span><span class="what"><b>tRAT.</b> Same ten items by team consensus, simultaneous reveal, appeals taken in writing.</span></li>
      <li><span class="clock">0:24 to 0:32</span><span class="what"><b>Clarification burst.</b> Address only the items that split teams. The likely split items are flagged in the Answer center.</span></li>
      <li><span class="clock">0:32 to 0:54</span><span class="what"><b>Application.</b> Read the stimulus, teams commit to A, B, or C, simultaneous reveal, then defend through the branch questions and cross examine.</span></li>
      <li><span class="clock">0:54 to 1:00</span><span class="what"><b>Debrief.</b> Name the single finding that decides the case, connect back to LO2 and LO3, preview the lab.</span></li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Discussion prompts for the application</h3>
    <ul class="plain">
      <li>What one finding in the stimulus most strongly separates a retroperitoneal source from an intraperitoneal one, and why does fluid behavior matter more than organ proximity here?</li>
      <li>If the abdomen had been rigid and distended with shifting dullness, which letter would become stronger, and what does that tell you about how intraperitoneal blood behaves?</li>
      <li>Trace the boundary a blade would cross to move from the flank into each of the three cavities in play. Name the structure at each boundary.</li>
      <li>Match each candidate source to its drainage or access procedure, and state why the cavity, not the organ, decides where the needle goes.</li>
    </ul>

    <h3>Common misconceptions the RAT will surface</h3>
    <p class="reading" style="font-size:14px;">Because every item integrates several concepts, a wrong answer usually marks a broken link between concepts, not a single missing fact. Watch for these.</p>
    <table class="s">
      <thead><tr><th style="width:60px;">Item</th><th>Integration failure to watch for and address</th></tr></thead>
      <tbody>
        <tr><td>Q1</td><td>Confusing the pleural and pericardial serous cavities, mislocating the heart's serous space outside the middle mediastinum, or matching the wrong access procedure to the cavity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q2</td><td>Generalizing one peritoneal relationship to both organs, missing that the spleen is intraperitoneal and the kidney retroperitoneal, then predicting the wrong bleed pattern from that error.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q3</td><td>Treating the epidermis as vascular, or anchoring it with the wrong structure. The epidermis is avascular and anchored to the basement membrane, fed by diffusion from the dermis.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q4</td><td>Linking an export protein to free ribosomes or smooth ER, or pairing a ductless endocrine cell with a holocrine or apocrine release mode rather than merocrine.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q5</td><td>Crediting the wrong stratum or the wrong cell with regeneration. The stratum basale and its keratinocytes do it, not the stratum corneum or melanocytes.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q6</td><td>Mismatching the germ layer, most connective tissue is mesoderm, or confusing dense regular with dense irregular collagen arrangement.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q7</td><td>Mixing the two cadherin junctions. The adherens belt links to microfilaments, the desmosome plaque links to intermediate filaments.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q8</td><td>Redefining proximal and distal, naming the wrong forearm region, or mapping a CT cross section to a plane other than transverse.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q9</td><td>Forgetting the mesothelium is simple squamous epithelium, or that the synovial membrane is the one body membrane with no epithelium.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q10</td><td>Swapping the lower quadrants for appendicitis and diverticulitis, or matching the peritoneal tap to the wrong cavity.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q11</td><td>Assuming goosebumps are voluntary, so the arrector pili must be skeletal muscle, or naming the hair root plexus, a nerve ending, as the muscle.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q12</td><td>Treating carotene, hemoglobin, or bilirubin as a type of melanin, or tying a skin color to the wrong pigment source.</td></tr>
        <tr><td>Q13</td><td>Reversing the anterior and posterior borders, or flipping the superior thoracic inlet with the inferior diaphragm.</td></tr>
      </tbody>
    </table>

    <div class="callout">
      <h4>Quick reference card, in play this session</h4>
      <ul class="plain" style="margin:0;">
        <li><b>Serous membranes.</b> Two layers, every time. The parietal layer lines the wall, the visceral layer covers the organ.</li>
        <li><b>SADPUCKER.</b> Suprarenals, Aorta and IVC, Duodenum (2 to 4), Pancreas (head, neck, body), Ureters, Colon (ascending and descending), Kidneys, Esophagus (abdominal segment), Rectum (lower).</li>
        <li><b>Cavity to needle.</b> Pleural to thoracentesis, pericardial to pericardiocentesis, peritoneal to paracentesis, vertebral to lumbar puncture.</li>
        <li><b>Bleed behavior.</b> Intraperitoneal blood spreads and irritates broadly, retroperitoneal blood stays hidden and presents as flank or back pain.</li>
      </ul>
    </div>
  </section>

