          <tr><td>12</td><td class="ans">C</td><td>2</td><td class="concept">Eumelanin and pheomelanin, skin color sources. Beyond Week 1.</td></tr>
          <tr><td>13</td><td class="ans">B</td><td>2</td><td class="concept">Directional terms applied to the mediastinal borders.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
      <p class="reading" style="font-size:13px;color:var(--teal-text);">Answer sequence for the core ten: C A D B C A B D A B. The additional items key A (Q11), C (Q12), and B (Q13). No identical answers fall consecutively in the running set.</p>

      <h3>Full per option rationales</h3>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q1. Serous layers, compartment, access route. Key: C</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>C is correct.</b> The serous cavity is the space between the parietal and visceral serous pericardium, the pericardium sits in the middle mediastinum, and that cavity is drained by pericardiocentesis. All three links hold.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Swaps the pericardium for the pleura, the wrong compartment, and thoracentesis, which drains the pleural cavity, not the pericardial.</li>
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Names the right cavity but the wrong compartment, the heart is in the middle, not the superior mediastinum, and pairs it with paracentesis, which taps the peritoneal cavity.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> The space between the epicardium and the fibrous pericardium is not the serous cavity, places the heart in the posterior mediastinum, and uses lumbar puncture, which samples the vertebral cavity. The likely split, since the epicardium is a real serous layer.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q2. LUQ organs, peritoneal relationship, bleed behavior. Key: A</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>A is correct.</b> In the LUQ the spleen is intraperitoneal, so its blood spreads freely and irritates the cavity, while the left kidney is retroperitoneal, so its blood stays contained behind the peritoneum and presents as flank pain. The relationship predicts the behavior.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Flips both relationships, the error of memorizing the organs but reversing which is intra and which is retro.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Over generalizes intraperitoneal to both, missing that the kidney is a SADPUCKER structure.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Over generalizes retroperitoneal to both, missing that the spleen is intraperitoneal.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q3. Epidermis classification, anchor, blood supply. Key: D</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>D is correct.</b> The epidermis is stratified squamous epithelium for protection, anchored to the basement membrane, and avascular, so it is fed by diffusion from the vessels in the dermis. Three properties, one tissue.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Picks simple squamous, which is built for diffusion not protection, names a mucous membrane as the anchor, and claims its own capillaries, contradicting the avascular epidermis.</li>
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Picks transitional, a urinary tract tissue, and calls it richly vascular, again contradicting the avascular fact.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Picks an airway tissue and names a mesentery as the anchor, a peritoneal structure that has nothing to do with the skin.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q4. Organelles, duct status, release mode. Key: B</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>B is correct.</b> A protein product is built on the rough ER and packaged by the Golgi, no duct means endocrine, and releasing the product intact by exocytosis is the merocrine mode. All three descriptors agree.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Smooth ER makes lipids not protein, exocrine requires a duct the stem rules out, and holocrine destroys the cell, which the stem also rules out.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Free ribosomes build cytosolic protein not export protein, and apocrine pinches off part of the cell rather than releasing intact.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Names the rough ER correctly but calls the cell exocrine, contradicting the no duct clue, and holocrine, contradicting the intact release.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q5. Strata, cell types, healing. Key: C</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>C is correct.</b> The stratum basale is the deepest, dividing layer, and its keratinocytes regenerate the epidermis when a wound spares it. The strata order and the cell job line up.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> The likely split. The stratum corneum is the dead surface layer, not the regenerating one, and melanocytes make pigment, they do not rebuild the epidermis.</li>
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> The stratum lucidum is a thin clear layer in thick skin only, and dendritic (Langerhans) cells are immune patrols, not regenerators.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> The stratum granulosum is where keratinization begins, not the dividing layer, and tactile (Merkel) cells serve touch, not regeneration.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q6. Connective subtype, germ layer, failure mode. Key: A</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>A is correct.</b> Parallel collagen strong in one direction is dense regular connective tissue, most connective tissue including tendon arises from mesoderm, and a tendon tears when twisted because its strength is one directional. A tendon satisfies all three clues.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Calls the tendon dense irregular, whose collagen runs in all directions, and assigns it to ectoderm, which forms epidermis and nervous tissue, not connective tissue.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> The dermis is dense irregular, not regular, and skin connective tissue is mesoderm, not endoderm.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Areolar is loose packing tissue, far too weak for a ligament that must bear a strong pull.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q7. Two cadherin junctions. Key: B</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>B is correct.</b> The adherens junction is the adhesion belt linked to microfilaments, and the desmosome is the plaque linked to intermediate filaments that rivets cells in the epidermis and cardiac muscle. Both use cadherins, which is the clue that narrows the field.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Tight junctions seal rather than form a belt, and gap junctions are communication channels, neither uses cadherins for the jobs described.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> The likely split. The desmosome is a plaque junction, not the belt, and the hemidesmosome anchors a cell to the basement membrane, not to a neighboring cell.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Gap and tight junctions are matched to roles that belong to the adherens junction and desmosome.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q8. Region, direction, imaging plane. Key: D</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>D is correct.</b> The forearm is the antebrachial region, distal means farther from the trunk, and a CT slice is a transverse section. All three readings are correct together.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Brachial is the arm not the forearm, distal does not mean closer to the trunk, and a frontal section divides anterior from posterior, not a CT cross section.</li>
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Names the region correctly but redefines proximal as farther from the trunk, the reverse of its meaning, and picks a sagittal section.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Carpal is the wrist, distal is misdefined, and the oblique plane does not give the clean cross section of a CT slice.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q9. Serous build, tissue, synovial comparison. Key: A</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>A is correct.</b> A serous membrane is the mesothelium, a simple squamous epithelium, over areolar connective tissue, and it differs from the synovial membrane, the one body membrane built from connective tissue alone with no epithelium.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Names stratified squamous rather than the simple squamous mesothelium, and wrongly equates serous and synovial membranes.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Picks an airway epithelium over fat, and the cutaneous membrane is the dry skin, a different membrane entirely.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Picks a urinary tract epithelium and confuses the serous membrane with a mucous membrane.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q10. LLQ pattern, peritoneal relationship, cavity access. Key: B</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>B is correct.</b> LLQ pain in an older adult points to diverticulitis, the sigmoid colon there is intraperitoneal, and the peritoneal cavity is sampled by paracentesis. The pattern, the relationship, and the procedure all agree.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Appendicitis is the right lower quadrant pattern, and thoracentesis drains the pleural cavity, not the peritoneal.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> The likely split. The descending colon is indeed retroperitoneal, but the organ behind LLQ diverticulitis is the sigmoid colon, which is intraperitoneal, and pericardiocentesis drains the heart sac, not the peritoneum.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Splenic injury is a left upper quadrant problem, and a lumbar puncture samples the vertebral cavity, not the peritoneal cavity.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q11. Arrector pili, muscle type, control. Key: A</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>A is correct.</b> The arrector pili is the small smooth muscle attached to a hair follicle, and like all smooth muscle it is involuntary, which is why goosebumps appear on their own rather than on command.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Names the right muscle but calls it skeletal and voluntary. The error is assuming you can raise a hair on purpose. The arrector pili is smooth muscle and acts involuntarily.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> The hair root plexus is the sensory nerve ending wrapped around the follicle that detects hair movement, not a muscle, so it cannot pull the hair upright.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> The erector spinae is a skeletal muscle of the back. A name that sounds similar is the trap, it has nothing to do with raising a hair.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q12. Melanin types and skin color. Key: C</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>C is correct.</b> The two forms of melanin are eumelanin, brown to black, and pheomelanin, red to yellow. A bluish skin color is the dark blood in the dermal vessels seen through the thin epidermis, an observation about what you are looking at, not the physiology behind it.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Carotene is a separate pigment source, not a type of melanin, and a bluish color is not caused by extra melanin.</li>
          <li><b>B wrong.</b> Hemoglobin is the blood pigment in the dermal vessels, not a melanin, and pallor is not produced by carotene.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Bilirubin is a separate pigment, not a melanin, and redness is not a loss of melanin.</li>
        </ul>
        <p class="reading" style="font-size:13px;color:var(--teal-text);margin-top:8px;">Scope note: eumelanin and pheomelanin and the diagnostic skin colors are not in the Week 1 notes. This item is held at the pigment and observation level. The causes of these colors are physiology and are left out.</p>
      </div>

      <div class="ratq">
        <p class="rq-stem">Q13. Directional terms and the mediastinal borders. Key: B</p>
        <p class="correct"><b>B is correct.</b> The sternum forms the anterior border, the bodies of the thoracic vertebrae form the posterior border, and the diaphragm forms the inferior border. The remaining two borders are the thoracic inlet superiorly and the mediastinal pleura laterally.</p>
        <ul class="why">
          <li><b>A wrong.</b> Reverses the front to back axis, putting the vertebrae anterior and the sternum posterior, and places the thoracic inlet inferiorly when it is the superior boundary.</li>
          <li><b>C wrong.</b> Flips the vertical axis. The diaphragm is the inferior border and the thoracic inlet the superior, not the reverse, and the sternum is anterior, not lateral.</li>
          <li><b>D wrong.</b> Scrambles several pairs. The diaphragm is inferior, not anterior, the vertebrae are posterior, not superior, and the mediastinal pleura forms the lateral borders, not the posterior.</li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <h3>Application defense guide</h3>
      <div class="callout navy">
        <h4>Best supported answer and how to adjudicate</h4>
        <p class="reading" style="margin:0 0 8px;">As written, the findings tilt toward <b>A, a retroperitoneal source</b>. Two findings carry the weight: the fluid does not move freely with position and sits against the posterior body wall, and the tenderness is localized to the flank and back rather than spreading across a soft abdomen. Both are the retroperitoneal signature from the notes, where a retroperitoneal bleed stays hidden and presents as flank or back pain.</p>
        <p class="reading" style="margin:0 0 8px;"><b>Honor a defended B</b> if a team argues the spleen sits in the left upper quadrant near this wound. Push back with the single finding that argues against it: a soft, non distended abdomen with fluid that does not move freely is not what free intraperitoneal blood from a splenic injury produces, since intraperitoneal blood spreads and irritates the whole cavity.</p>
        <p class="reading" style="margin:0;"><b>Honor a defended C</b> if a team reasons from the rib level. A wound below the 12th rib can cross the diaphragm into the pleural cavity because the diaphragm domes upward, so a thoracic injury can hide behind an abdominal entry point. The decisive teaching point: the cavity reached, not the entry skin region, sets the access procedure, pleural to thoracentesis, peritoneal to paracentesis.</p>
      </div>

      <h3>DOK verification summary</h3>
      <p class="reading" style="font-size:13.5px;">With only ten items, every item is built to require reasoning across two to four concepts at once, so the correct answer cannot be reached by isolating one fact. Nine items are DOK 3, where the scenario is novel, the student weighs competing options, and the distractors break a specific link between concepts that a partial understanding would still find plausible, Q1 through Q7, Q9, and Q10. One item, Q8, is DOK 2, an applied read of a chart and an imaging plane across three vocabularies. No item is answerable by recall alone, and none requires the multi step clinical decision making reserved for the application exercise. Several items meet the DOK 4 integration test on their face, since the key requires connecting at least two content domains, but they are held at the readiness assurance level by testing the connection between foundational concepts rather than a full clinical decision.</p>
